{"key":"post-11512759","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11512759</id>\n<content>Get some petri dishes.&amp;nbsp; I've yet to see anyone do a successful strain isolation on agar using jars.&amp;nbsp; Petri dishes are ten to fifteen cents each, and jars are nearly a dollar each.&amp;nbsp; Use jars for grains or brf and petri dishes for agar.&amp;nbsp; You're going to need a few dozen to get started, and the jars use up a lot of real estate.&amp;nbsp; In addition, the CO2 builds up in the bottom of the jar, choking the mycelium.&amp;nbsp; Petri dishes are shallow and this problem doesn't occur.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Using jars instead of petri dishes is like using a pair of pliers to drive in a nail instead of a hammer.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11512956</next>\n<prev>11512740</prev>\n<first>11512339</first>\n<last>11520144</last>\n<when>1259020444</when>\n<utime>11/24/09 01:54 AM</utime>\n</post>"}